summary: The second season of this drama opens with Carrie ( AnnaSophia Robb ) and her pal Walt ( Brendan Dooling ) enjoying the summer in New York City. While trying to get into a club one night, Carrie meets a new and slightly older friend: the wild and street-smart Samantha Jones (Lindsey Gort), who temporarily becomes her roommate. Before long, Carrie begins her senior year of high school while continuing her job at the magazine. At work, she's tasked with interviewing playwright Adam Weaver (Chris Woods), and a romance between the two of them soon develops. Meanwhile, Walt begins dating Bennet (Jake Robinson), who learns that his ex-boyfriend now has AIDS. As graduation looms, Carrie and her dad (Matt Letscher) butt heads over the topic of college.

Based on Candace Bushnell's young-adult book series of the same name, this prequel to "Sex and the City" focuses on teenage Carrie Bradshaw (AnnaSophia Robb) growing up in suburban Connecticut in the 1980s. Series 1 finds Carrie and her family still reeling from the recent death of Carrie's mom. One bright spot for Carrie is the start of her new internship at a law firm in Manhattan. While in the city, Carrie meets fashion editor and party gal Larissa (Freema Agyeman), who mistakes Carrie for someone older and becomes her mentor. Carrie then tries juggling her wild new experiences in New York City with her ordinary high-school life, where she hangs out with pals Maggie (Katie Findlay), Mouse (Ellen Wong) and Walt (Brendan Dooling). She also becomes attracted to Sebastian (Austin Butler), the troubled new boy who got kicked out of his old school. As the season progresses, the balancing act gets tougher, and Carrie begins finding her voice through her journal writing.

Season 2 opens as Cad Bane infiltrates the Jedi Temple and attempts to steal an ancient Jedi Holocron. It's up to Ahsoka, Anakin and Obi-Wan to stop the bounty hunter from escaping with the valuable Jedi artifact.

Yoda, Anakin and the Jedi Knights fight in the Clone Wars, taking them to many new planets and introducing new players. The series spans the time between 'Star Wars Episode II: Attack of the Clones' and 'Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith.'

Season 4 of this animated series opens with the Ghost crew attempting to rescue Sabine's father, who is being held captive. After the mission, Ezra, Kanan and Sabine join the Rebel Alliance on the planet Yavin 4. But when news breaks that the Empire is building a secret weapon in Lothal, Ezra and his crew head back home. Now, they must face the Imperial forces, under the command of Grand Admiral Thrawn, with the help of some old acquaintances.

Season 3 of this animated series opens six months after the events of the previous season. Ezra, now more powerful and with a new lightsaber, leads a rescue mission. Meanwhile, Kanan is struggling with his blindness. However, after a fateful encounter, he learns a valuable lesson in the Force. Throughout the season, the Ghost crew fight for new resources and enlist new recruits, planning a direct assault on the Empire. The Empire, though, have plans of their own. They are now being led by Grand Admiral Thrawn, a threat unlike any other the group has ever seen.

In the second season of this animated series, the evil Empire is closing in on the Rebel forces. The crew of the Ghost are forced to leave planet Lothal in order to survive and fight another day, but not before a dangerous battle against Darth Vader leaves most of the team badly injured. Now, the group must join forces with another rebel cell, led by the Jedi Ahsoka Tano. Meanwhile, new Inquisitors are sent to track down and defeat the expanding rebellion. With new allies on their side, the group get involved in more dangerous missions, risking their lives to bring down the Empire once and for all.

The animated series set in the "Star Wars" universe follows the crew of the Ghost, a ship used by the Rebellion in their fight against the Empire. The crew includes: Ezra, a force-sensitive 15-year-old orphan; Kanan, a Jedi who survived Order 66 and who becomes Ezra's Master; Hera, the pilot of the ship; Sabine, a weapon expert who once was on her way to become an Imperial soldier; Zeb, a warrior who saw his homeworld destroyed and his people massacred; Chopper, the ship's droid. Season 1 starts five years before "A New Hope" and chronicles the Ghost's travels through the Galaxy as its crew finds ways to survive and overthrow the Empire.

Secrecy and lies drive this 1940s period drama about the birth of the nuclear age, and the fictitious stories of the men and women involved in the clandestine race to build the world's first atomic bomb. The series focuses on the moral dilemmas faced by a ragtag team of scientists headed by brilliant nuclear physicist Frank Winter (John Benjamin Hickey) after they, along with their families, are relocated to the remote desert of Los Alamos, New Mexico, to work on the top-secret Manhattan Project. Season 2 sees Charlie is forced into a new leadership role in the race to build the world's first atomic bomb.

The series focuses on the moral dilemmas faced by a ragtag team of scientists headed by brilliant nuclear physicist Frank Winter (John Benjamin Hickey) after they, along with their families, are relocated to the remote desert of Los Alamos, N.M., to work on the top-secret Manhattan Project. For loved ones, asking questions is frowned upon, but that doesn't keep Frank's botanist wife Liza (Olivia Williams) from making some frightening discoveries about the local environment. Meanwhile, her marriage to Frank suffers as he becomes consumed by his mission. Daniel Stern, Ashley Zukerman, Katja Herbers and Rachel Brosnahan also star.

More than six years have passed since Praimfaya has ravaged the planet and killed most of the human race. As Clarke waits to hear from the group on the Ark, or in the bunker, a prison ship drops from the sky. Are they friend or foe?  And what do they want?

The fourth season of The CW's post-apocalyptic science fiction series continues to chronicle the lives of a group of former juvenile delinquents who were sent away from the space colony that was their home in order to repopulate the Earth, which had been uninhabited by humans for a century following a nuclear fallout. Over the years, the fight to survive has led to lives full of betrayal, fear, and loss for Bellamy (Bob Morley), Clarke (Eliza Taylor), and the rest of their group. And a devastating revelation has made their future all the more uncertain.

Based on a series of books by Kass Morgan, this dystopian science fiction series follows 100 teenagers who are sent back to repopulate the Earth almost a century after an apocalyptic nuclear event forced humanity to flee the planet. Picking up three months after the tragic events of the previous season's finale, the third season finds Bellamy (Bob Morley), Kane (Henry Ian Cusick), and others undertaking a dangerous mission to rescue Clarke (Eliza Taylor) from a looming threat to her life. Also starring Paige Turco, Lindsey Morgan, and Ricky Whittle.

In Season 2 Clarke escapes and finds out that there is a large amount of human survivors on the planet, but they haven't built up a resistance to radiation like the 100 have. Meanwhile, Chancellor Jaha finds a baby in the Ark and plans to go to the Earth. However, he crash lands and is later rescued by a boy called Zoran who is in search of the City of Light with his parents.

Juvenile prisoners from a space-station society are exiled to Earth decades after the planet was destroyed by nuclear war in this sci-fi adventure. In the first series, an antibiotic is sought to treat Jasper (Devon Bostick), and Bellamy (Bob Morley) struggles to maintain order. Later, Raven (Lindsey Morgan) notices a connection between Finn (Thomas McDonell) and Clarke (Eliza Taylor), while Kane (Henry Ian Cusick) wrestles with guilt over a difficult decision. Marie Avgeropoulos, Paige Turco, Isaiah Washington and Eli Goree also star in Series 1.

A vapid model who met an untimely death returns to the living in the body of a plus-size attorney.

Jane (Brooke Elliott) learns "Old Jane" is back on earth in the body of beautiful model Brittney (Natalie Hall), and tries to maintain a professional relationship with ex-fianc Owen (Lex Medlin) in the fifth season of this comedy-drama.

Beautiful model Deb continues to live the life of brilliant, plus-size attorney Jane Bingum (Brooke Elliott) in the fourth season of this comedy-drama. Some of the cases she works on include representing a young woman who wants out of an arranged marriage to a Bhutanese prince, defending a family friend from murder charges and taking on the case of a woman who is addicted to eating her dead husband's ashes. Also, drama ensues as she prepares for her upcoming marriage to Owen (Lex Medlin). Kim Kardashian has a recurring role as Nikki LePree this season.

Season 3 follows Deb as she learns to adjust to living the life of brilliant, plus-size attorney Jane Bingum (Brooke Elliott). Being her former lover's best friend in her new life is not as easy as it seems when she promises to be the best man at his wedding. She also has many complicated cases to work on, including defending a man who held her up at gunpoint, representing a high-school lesbian couple who are not permitted to attend prom and getting justice for a bride-to-be who was trampled at a bridal super sale.

Season 2 continues to follow beautiful but shallow model Deb living in the body of brilliant, hard-working and plus-size attorney Jane Bingum (Brooke Elliott). As she attempts to move on from her feelings for Grayson (Jackson Hurst), she also has to contend with her boss, Jay Parker (Josh Stamberg), hooking up with her rival Kim (Kate Levering). Paula Abdul and Rosie O'Donnell continue to guest star this season as judges.

Season 1 of this legal comedy-drama begins when beautiful but shallow model Deb (Brooke D'Orsay) dies in a car accident. When she returns to the land of the living, she does so as the brilliant, hard-working and plus-size attorney Jane Bingum (Brooke Elliott). Deb faces many hurdles as she adjusts to Jane's life, including working with the former love of her life, Grayson (Jackson Hurst), as he mourns her death and attempts to move on, dealing with Jane's coworker and rival Kim (Kate Levering) and learning valuable lessons about inner beauty and personal acceptance. Luckily, she has April (Stacy Barrett), her best friend and the only human who knows her predicament, and Fred (Ben Feldman), her guardian angel, to help support and guide her through the ups and downs of her new life. Paula Abdul and Rosie O'Donnell both have recurring roles as judges throughout the season.
